sentences: William Patrick Foster (August 25, 1919 – August 28, 2010), also known as The Law and The Maestro, was the director of the noted Florida A&M University Marching "100".
Foster brought over 30 new techniques to the band, which have now become standard procedure for high school and college bands nationwide.
In 1989, the French chose Foster and his band as America's official representative in the Bastille Day Parade, celebrating the bicentennial of the French Revolution.
In January 1993 and 1997, the band appeared in the Inaugural Parade of President Bill Clinton.
While educators saw bands as a way to teach music to large numbers of students, few college bands existed around the turn of the century.

Foster has been credited with developing at least 30 new marching band techniques, including the double-time marching step of 240 steps per minute or four steps per second, and the triple-time marching step of 360 steps per minute, the death-slow cadence of 20 steps per minute or one step every three seconds, and memorization of all music played in stands, parades, pre-game and halftime shows.
He is the composer of Marche Brillante, National Honors March, March Continental, and Centennial Celebration.
He died on August 28, 2010 at 12:01 AM.
He was 91 years old.
